To show that the integral in the last line converges we use the asymptotics (13.8.12) of \cite{DLMF}, which, in our case reads as
\begin{multline}\label{asymM}\frac{M(\frac{k-1}{2}+s, k, 2 \pi n)}{\Gamma(k)}= \left (\frac{2 \pi n}{\frac{k-1}{2}+s} \right )^{\frac{1-k}{2}}\frac{\Gamma \left (\frac{1-k}{2}+s \right )}{\Gamma \left (\frac{k-1}{2}+s \right )}e^{\pi n}I_{k-1}(\sqrt{8 \pi n(\frac{k-1}{2}+s)})(1+O(s^{-1}))\\
+\sqrt{\frac{2 \pi n}{\frac{k-1}{2}+s}}I_{k}(\sqrt{8 \pi n (\frac{k-1}{2}+s)})(s+O(1)).
\end{multline}
The asymptotics of $I_{k-1}(z)$ and $I_{k}(z)$ ((10.40.5) \cite{DLMF}) show that they are dominated by $e^{z}$ as $z \to \infty$. Therefore, if $8 \pi n(\frac{k-1}{2}+s)=r e^{i\theta}$, then, for $|t|=|\Im(s)| \to \infty$, 
$$I_{k-1}(\sqrt{8 \pi n(\frac{k-1}{2}+s)}) \ll e^{\sqrt{8 \pi n(\frac{k-1}{2}+s)}}=
|e^{\sqrt{r}e^{i\theta/2}}| \le e^{C\sqrt{n|t|}}.
$$
This, together with \eqref{asymM} shows that the integrand in \eqref{I2} is
$$\ll_{n, X, \varepsilon} \frac{\Gamma \left (\frac{k+1}{s}-s \right )\Gamma(s)}{\Gamma(s+\rho+1)} \frac{\Gamma \left (\frac{1-k}{2}+s \right )}{\Gamma \left (\frac{k-1}{2}+s \right )}e^{C\sqrt{n|t|}},$$ for some $C>0$, as $|t| \to \infty$. Since, by Stirling's formula the Gamma quotient is $\ll e^{-\frac{\pi}{2}|t|}$, we deduce that the integrand is $\ll e^{-C_1 \sqrt{|t|}}$ for some $C_1>0$, as $|t| \to \infty$ and hence the integral in \eqref{I2} converges. {\bf To complete the proof that the series in \eqref{I2} converges (and, at the same time, justify the interchange of summation/integration mentioned above) we need \emph{uniform} asymptotics for $M(a, b, s)$, which I haven't found yet. Any suggestions?}
\end{proof} 




